Data Exploration:

Structure of the Dataset:

The dataset includes a large amount of variables. Some of these variables are aggregate variables (made from a combination of other variables) and some do not make sense to include in the prediction model from a domain perspective. Also, some variables may not be relevant to our prediciton. After exploration and cleaning, we can use logistic regression to remove the variables with little to no influence.

Analysis of Amount Funded

We begin by examining the distribution of amount funded for each succesful loan. Here we plot the count for each amount funded. We find that the majority of the people are looking for smaller loans, and it trails out towards the upper limits of ~35,000. Another interesting thing to note is the spikes at each interval of 5000. ### Analysis of income range description

## Warning: Removed 4 rows containing non-finite values (stat_count).

Here we plot the distribution of the income ranges for the borrowers. We find that it does not necessarily follow a normal distribution, with the majority of the borrows have less than 75,000.

For predictive purposes we will go ahead and assume that incomplete loans which are paid per schedule will be completed per schedule. Similarly, we will convert loans which are sold off to colleciton agencies as defaulted.

Time Analysis

We look to explore how the the different variables differ over time.

Analysis per Month

We will start by analysing the potential variation in the amount of loans taken and proportion of defaults among financial quarters. This bar chart is highly interesting, as it seems as if people tend to increasingly take out loans as the year progresses.

Analysis By Monthly Quarter Exploration

Additionally, it seems as if the rate of default is lower as the year progresses, especially in the last financial quarter. To test this hypothesis we will calculate and plot the actual numbers for proportion of default.

## [1] 0.1611894
## [1] 0.1383878
## [1] 0.1266747
## [1] 0.1180214

Here it becomes entirely clear to us that the rate of default substantially decreases with each financial quarter. This is a valuable finding which calls for further exploration.

Default by Month Analysis

We will proceed by redoing the previous analysis per month. This could potentially show us whether certain months are drivers of the increased amount of loans and decreased default rates. It appears as if there is near linear growth from January until September, which is quite interesting in itself. Additionally, for November and December there appears to be a non-proportional growth in default rates, which could be an option for arbitrage.

Lets continue by calculating the default rates. As suspected, the default rates of especially November and December are substantially lower than other months.

Default Rate vs Borrow Rate vs Month: Arbitrage Opportunity

However, to check whether an investor would be able to find opportunity for arbitrage here, one would need to measure up the rate of default to the interest rate of loans. It could be that the months of November and December are simply filled with ideal loan candidates, demanding low borrowing rates. Lets try to roughly estimate how the two match up over the year. It here becomes clear to us that there does not seem to be a significant enough drop in borrowing rate for November and December to divert from investing in November and December. In conclusion, we believe to have found significant arbitrage opportunities for future investing.

Top 500 cities by GPD Analysis

Another aspect of location that we wanted to explore was cities. Since there were so many cities, we realized we needed to reduce this to a more measurable aspect. To do this, we took a dataset from Bureau of Economic Analysis which provided a list of the top 500 metropolotian areas with the best GDP. We parsed the cities from this and then created a new factor that marks each city as either major GDP or not major GDP.

After separating the cities into two groups, either in the top 500 gpd producing metros or not major, we find little correlation.
